1
00:00:04,992 --> 00:00:13,348
Namo dasa bhavato arahato samasambuddhasa

2
00:00:13,564 --> 00:00:36,518
Namo tassa bhagavato arhato samasambuddhasam Namo tassa bhagavato arhato samasambuddhasam Homage to the Buddha, the blessed, noble and fully self-enlightened one.

3
00:00:43,484 --> 00:00:49,892
And we had two escapees, Liam and Grace, decided it was too early.

4
00:00:52,475 --> 00:00:56,340
So that's why we're here, just in case you wondered why we're here.

5
00:00:58,182 --> 00:01:10,757
So I thought we'd take a little journey around the Buddha's teachings, try to get a fulsome picture of it, if you will.

6
00:01:13,572 --> 00:01:20,361
And all his teaching really is contained in what we call these four noble truths, these four truths.

7
00:01:21,944 --> 00:01:32,457
The first one is this core word of his, dukkha, which translates as hard to bear.

8
00:01:37,433 --> 00:01:48,543
And the question is, you know, do we cause our own suffering or is that caused by the world, something out there?

9
00:01:49,545 --> 00:01:52,248
So we've already looked at that within ourselves.

10
00:01:53,209 --> 00:02:07,102
And what we're trying to discern very clearly is this distinction between the fact that life is hard to bear, shall we say, on an ordinary basis,

11
00:02:07,436 --> 00:02:12,506
daily basis and in a lifelong basis.

12
00:02:12,526 --> 00:02:23,104
Every day we have to get up, we have to go to work and if you haven't got work, you're anxious about getting work and it's like it's a daily grind.

13
00:02:25,868 --> 00:02:30,997
Very fortunate if you enjoy your work or if work is well paid and so on.

14
00:02:32,193 --> 00:02:37,381
But even that has its ups and downs.

15
00:02:37,401 --> 00:02:44,591
A job that we enter with great enthusiasm, in a couple of months becomes boring.

16
00:02:45,431 --> 00:02:52,141
And there's also a much deeper sort of pain about life, which is the process of falling ill.

17
00:02:53,707 --> 00:02:55,311
aging and dying.

18
00:02:55,872 --> 00:03:06,370
So it's not as though we're ever going to make this life form any easier through the process of liberation.

19
00:03:06,389 --> 00:03:08,013
That's not where the liberation lies.

20
00:03:08,514 --> 00:03:15,766
The Buddha himself grew old and died of quite a painful gastroenteritis.

21
00:03:16,793 --> 00:03:19,116
He didn't escape any of the ailments.

22
00:03:19,296 --> 00:03:20,838
I'm sure he had more illnesses than that.

23
00:03:20,859 --> 00:03:22,442
Well, at one point he was healed.

24
00:03:23,182 --> 00:03:28,711
And somebody came and reminded him that just contemplating the seven factors of enlightenment would help.

25
00:03:29,572 --> 00:03:34,439
And he became better because of that.

26
00:03:34,460 --> 00:03:42,632
So it's not as though the Buddha is saying that there is a liberation from the aches and pains and the process of living.

27
00:03:43,219 --> 00:03:49,667
On the other hand, he's not saying that life doesn't offer us pleasures, joys and happiness.

28
00:03:51,027 --> 00:04:03,100
And when we think about happiness and our search for happiness, you can normally put it into three types of happiness, I think.

29
00:04:03,161 --> 00:04:11,370
The first one is just the ordinary sensual pleasure of having a meal or chocolate, you know.

30
00:04:11,889 --> 00:04:19,680
And then there's a sort of more engrossed type of happiness where we enter into an absorption of what we're doing.

31
00:04:20,721 --> 00:04:34,759
And all these dangerous sports are really based on people who are getting that high buzz of losing themselves just for that dangerous moment in a perfect state of excited happiness.

32
00:04:35,076 --> 00:04:45,266
A lot, I mean, every time we might watch a DVD or something, the underlying attitude would be to lose yourself in the film.

33
00:04:46,447 --> 00:04:52,050
And then when you come out, of course, you know, it's been a great film, it's a good film.

34
00:04:52,071 --> 00:04:58,797
So, on that type of happiness, which is a deeper level, of course you lose it as soon as you become aware of it.

35
00:04:59,718 --> 00:05:04,442
It's one of those paradoxes, that we're most happy at that level, and we don't know it.

36
00:05:05,485 --> 00:05:10,095
But there is of course a much deeper level of happiness and that has to do with meaningfulness.

37
00:05:10,851 --> 00:05:18,038
And when it comes to deep meaningfulness, we're talking about some sort of deep connection with life.

38
00:05:18,418 --> 00:05:20,480
We're asking the question, why am I here?

39
00:05:21,380 --> 00:05:32,750
At its most acute example, it would be these people who are quite prepared to undergo imprisonment, torture, etc.

40
00:05:32,810 --> 00:05:34,473
for political freedom.

41
00:05:35,293 --> 00:05:40,317
Just thinking of one case of Burma and the sufferings of Aung San Suu Kyi.

42
00:05:40,298 --> 00:05:52,781
Her willingness to bear all sorts of indignities, imprisonment, not to be able to be by the side of her husband when he was dying.

43
00:05:53,262 --> 00:05:57,108
She could leave them, but of course she let them back in.

44
00:05:57,358 --> 00:05:58,701
And they wouldn't let him come.

45
00:05:59,262 --> 00:06:02,305
So it was a point of anguish for her, I'm sure.

46
00:06:02,865 --> 00:06:13,980
And even more anguish to know that her close supporters were actually being treated far worse than ever she was, because as an international figure they had to be slightly careful.

47
00:06:14,000 --> 00:06:17,545
Many were tortured, tortured to death, and so on and so forth.

48
00:06:17,565 --> 00:06:25,797
These people, the unknowns, the ones that are sort of nameless, whom, in a sense, she symbolizes...

49
00:06:26,214 --> 00:06:48,920
have found a sort of tremendous courage, a deep commitment which comes not from any attempt to find sensual pleasure or to be in one of these beautiful high states, but because of some deep meaningfulness within them.

50
00:06:51,141 --> 00:06:55,766
And one of our problems for, she would say, a lot of people

51
00:06:55,915 --> 00:07:06,093
who've lost the connection with religion, is that there's that sense of loss, of a deep meaningfulness about their lives.

52
00:07:06,795 --> 00:07:12,384
Hence the huge new religion of consumerism everybody's into.

53
00:07:12,526 --> 00:07:18,716
And with the understanding that, you know, well, life is meaningless, or whatever, so I may as well enjoy myself.

54
00:07:19,372 --> 00:07:35,649
But that layering of that deep sense of meaninglessness, with pleasure of course, eventually caves in because there comes a point where sickness, aging, and the fact of death hits us.

55
00:07:36,288 --> 00:07:45,918
And I would have thought that underlying meaninglessness is actually a state of despair.

56
00:07:46,911 --> 00:07:50,898
And I think that's what the Buddha felt when he first started his search.

57
00:07:50,918 --> 00:07:51,959
I think he felt that.

58
00:07:54,083 --> 00:08:13,172
The idea of constantly coming back to the reborn, just a constant flow of this energy, reborn, reborn, this human being or that animal or that god, whatever, with no end in sight, was meaningless.

59
00:08:13,759 --> 00:08:26,571
I think that we have it in our Western culture through the existentialists who saw the idea of being conscious, being conscious.

60
00:08:26,720 --> 00:08:30,824
For no reason, having lost any connection with religion.

61
00:08:32,845 --> 00:08:39,812
People like maybe Jean-Paul Sartre or Camus would have said that it's completely meaningless.

62
00:08:39,831 --> 00:08:43,894
So they had this word, this absurd, it was absurd.

63
00:08:45,917 --> 00:08:51,142
And so this drive towards meaningfulness is really what we're doing.

64
00:08:51,481 --> 00:08:54,684
We're trying to find out why in the hell we're here.

65
00:08:55,205 --> 00:09:05,254
We might like to say to ourselves that we know, but the real test is when you face death, because death is the end of everything you know.

66
00:09:05,274 --> 00:09:24,434
And when we face that possibility, that there is an end point to this apparition, this person that I appear from moment to moment, day to day, and I give myself a name, I have a passport, and it all seems very real,

67
00:09:24,414 --> 00:09:41,482
comes to this point where, you know, everything that I have achieved, you know, all the wealth and the power and the object and all my clothes and all that are all left behind.

68
00:09:41,724 --> 00:09:43,706
It all just disappears.

69
00:09:45,239 --> 00:09:56,990
It was like the solicitor was asked how much the old widow had left, and he said, everything.

70
00:09:57,010 --> 00:10:00,835
So, that gives you an idea of the finality of death.

71
00:10:01,434 --> 00:10:08,842
And, you know, one way to really break through the illusion is the contemplation of death.

72
00:10:08,863 --> 00:10:11,144
It's a very strong contemplation.

73
00:10:11,547 --> 00:10:13,850
And it's there in a later commentary.

74
00:10:13,870 --> 00:10:14,971
Well, the Buddha has it.

75
00:10:14,991 --> 00:10:15,592
What am I saying?

76
00:10:15,894 --> 00:10:30,635
It's in a commentary where this Suddhibhadra, Buddhaghosa, so this would have been, as you were saying, a practice that people would have had, and people do have now, of just keep repeating the word death.

77
00:10:33,316 --> 00:10:34,457
He says that's enough.

78
00:10:35,038 --> 00:10:46,014
But the Buddha makes it even more obvious, because we were talking about the discourse on how to establish mindfulness.

79
00:10:46,035 --> 00:10:51,364
We were talking about the body, that the first part is about the body, and it's split into various sections.

80
00:10:51,423 --> 00:10:52,586
First of all, there's the breath.

81
00:10:53,086 --> 00:10:56,150
There's one about actions, which I stretched yesterday.

82
00:10:56,130 --> 00:11:01,657
But there's also one about the cemetery observations.

83
00:11:02,317 --> 00:11:10,067
In those days, bodies were laid out in a charnel ground, and they were left to rot, eaten by animals, etc.

84
00:11:10,847 --> 00:11:20,239
And those who really wanted to face the meaning of death would go and sit and observe the corruption of the body.

85
00:11:20,799 --> 00:11:25,125
And he has that, I think it's 11 or 13 stages where

86
00:11:25,561 --> 00:11:29,907
But you can see the body slowly corrupting finally ending up as just dust.

87
00:11:32,009 --> 00:11:42,764
The commentary gives a very worthwhile comment or piece of advice saying that if you do this practice you shouldn't sit in wood.

88
00:11:43,725 --> 00:11:52,977
So when you find a dead body and have a look at it make sure the wind is coming from behind.

89
00:11:53,719 --> 00:11:55,280
Just as a little aside

90
00:11:56,256 --> 00:12:04,669
There was a European monk, I don't know what nationality he was, who wanted to take that contemplation seriously.

91
00:12:04,710 --> 00:12:15,666
And he was able to get permission, the last thing I know, to take a convict's body that had died and carry it on his back to his cave.

92
00:12:15,645 --> 00:12:25,442
And in his cave, or the outing cave, he built a glass container which had a chimney going up.

93
00:12:26,202 --> 00:12:38,903
And when it became known that this was happening, the newspapers went gung-ho on it and said, finally, a real monk was located.

94
00:12:38,883 --> 00:12:49,774
And I don't know what happened during that time, but the end of the story is that he left the order and went to work for Mother Teresa in Calcutta.

95
00:12:50,394 --> 00:12:55,580
So that to me sounds as though something happened in that contemplation.

96
00:12:56,801 --> 00:13:05,429
Perhaps it reconnected him with life and preciousness of life.

97
00:13:05,590 --> 00:13:06,291
Who knows?

98
00:13:06,811 --> 00:13:10,379
There is that about life.

99
00:13:12,143 --> 00:13:13,767
It's deep meaningfulness.

100
00:13:13,966 --> 00:13:17,014
What is the purpose of our lives?

101
00:13:17,775 --> 00:13:22,125
At that deep level of just being a human being.

102
00:13:22,566 --> 00:13:24,650
Why are we here?

103
00:13:26,182 --> 00:13:40,767
And when the Buddha says this, it even gets even more subtle because once we begin to access the position within us of the observer,

104
00:13:41,100 --> 00:13:57,369
And we begin to recognize that the observer in that state, when we're there, you see, and you have to make it sort of plain to yourself through the practice, that when you're in that state, there is no felt suffering.

105
00:13:58,490 --> 00:14:01,916
Everything that you're feeling is observed as an object.

106
00:14:02,277 --> 00:14:07,125
And therefore, the observer is no longer in a state of suffering.

107
00:14:09,080 --> 00:14:17,653
And it is said that such is the state of peace within that state that even a moment of consciousness is felt as a disturbance.

108
00:14:20,238 --> 00:14:31,154
So this feeling of unsatisfactoriness, it goes really very, very deep.

109
00:14:32,164 --> 00:14:35,769
And this is what the Buddha, you know, he saw.

110
00:14:36,410 --> 00:14:48,107
But in the next Noble Truth he points to at least the psychological reason as to why we're unhappy with this situation.

111
00:14:49,769 --> 00:14:52,013
And that is to do with his desire

112
00:14:52,211 --> 00:15:03,375
And when we look at desire, which we've been looking at through all our practices, we always find that there's an I in front of it.

113
00:15:03,674 --> 00:15:06,120
There's always I desire something.

114
00:15:06,639 --> 00:15:18,099
Luckily, through our practice, say around eating, we can actually observe desire long enough to know that in fact the I doesn't have to attach itself.

115
00:15:18,700 --> 00:15:21,784
Our sense of identity really doesn't have to happen.

116
00:15:22,405 --> 00:15:27,413
We can just feel the desire and just allow it to peter out.

117
00:15:29,397 --> 00:15:31,179
That of course is the escape.

118
00:15:31,649 --> 00:15:35,778
That's the escape from the suffering that's caused through this desire.

119
00:15:36,399 --> 00:15:41,610
But this desire, remember, is rooted in a very good reason.

120
00:15:42,052 --> 00:15:44,798
The very good reason is to enjoy life.

121
00:15:45,259 --> 00:15:46,702
That's all we want to do.

122
00:15:46,722 --> 00:15:49,168
I mean, when we get down to it, I just want to be happy.

123
00:15:50,852 --> 00:15:57,381
And the happiness is, you know, to be found in the world.

124
00:15:57,481 --> 00:15:58,923
That's the presumption.

125
00:16:00,145 --> 00:16:09,198
You know, I'm living here, I've got this body and it gives me certain pleasures and I have friends, etc, etc, and I just want to be happy.

126
00:16:09,719 --> 00:16:18,289
But the happiness is based on a deep connection, a deep, excuse me, a deep delusion as to who or what I am.

127
00:16:18,951 --> 00:16:21,674
And that's my sense of me, my I.

128
00:16:22,535 --> 00:16:29,144
Now, when you're in the state of the observer, there's still that sense of some body observer.

129
00:16:29,850 --> 00:16:36,200
So right there, right when we've pulled out of the body because we're looking at sensations of feeling.

130
00:16:36,220 --> 00:16:41,548
Right when we've pulled out of emotions because we can feel emotions, see it and observe it.

131
00:16:42,249 --> 00:16:51,522
Right when we've pulled out of the mind, this may be a bit difficult over the weekend, but where you can actually observe just images passing in front of you.

132
00:16:51,501 --> 00:16:54,047
Or even a thought, you know.

133
00:16:55,029 --> 00:17:09,240
When you've pulled out of all that physical, psychological stuff that's going on, and you've arrived at this observation post within yourself, still there's a sense of somebody watching.

134
00:17:10,250 --> 00:17:11,531
And that's where it begins.

135
00:17:11,771 --> 00:17:20,541
It begins right there, with that awareness feeling itself as itself in the mind.

136
00:17:20,582 --> 00:17:22,805
It's like a mirror image.

137
00:17:22,825 --> 00:17:26,470
It's like when you look into a mirror, you see your face.

138
00:17:26,490 --> 00:17:32,215
And we always think that's the way people see us.

139
00:17:32,237 --> 00:17:35,160
Now, how many of you have done the two mirror trick?

140
00:17:39,358 --> 00:17:46,108
You're in for a big shock.

141
00:17:46,128 --> 00:18:04,895
The two-mirror trick is, you look into the mirror, you get a mirror which looks at your object, at your face in the mirror, and you're looking at this, at the way people actually see you, because the mirror turns your face around.

142
00:18:05,215 --> 00:18:06,278
And it can be a shock.

143
00:18:06,298 --> 00:18:08,421
You never thought your nose would be that big.

144
00:18:09,193 --> 00:18:11,978
It's like when you first hear your voice recording.

145
00:18:12,578 --> 00:18:19,910
Or worse, to see yourself on video, as always, a tremendous shock.

146
00:18:20,549 --> 00:18:36,113
So, this awareness, this intuitive awareness that we access in, purer and purer, through our meditation, feels its presence in the mind.

147
00:18:36,817 --> 00:18:43,987
And it even has an object, a very fine object of a sense of I.

148
00:18:44,548 --> 00:18:49,433
And that's where you get this feeling of some body observing, some body feeling.

149
00:18:51,616 --> 00:19:06,234
Then, of course, because it sees itself in the mirror, and this is Alice through the looking glass, sees itself in the mirror, or better still, like Narcissus,

150
00:19:06,619 --> 00:19:11,486
Narcissus who looked in the pool and saw his face and fell in love with himself.

151
00:19:12,066 --> 00:19:15,009
Went and roused himself and fell into the water and drowned.

152
00:19:15,029 --> 00:19:19,795
Do you know that is exactly what's happening?

153
00:19:19,855 --> 00:19:20,977
That's exactly what's happening.

154
00:19:20,997 --> 00:19:30,567
From moment to moment we look into the mind and heart and we embrace it entirely and fall into the waters of life.

155
00:19:31,729 --> 00:19:36,474
And we're constantly becoming this poor drowning object

156
00:19:36,843 --> 00:19:39,928
in a stream of life's consciousness.

157
00:19:39,948 --> 00:19:41,049
Because that's all it is.

158
00:19:41,069 --> 00:19:44,575
It's just a flow of these moments and moments of consciousness.

159
00:19:45,737 --> 00:19:55,813
So, that attraction, that attraction that draws us there is because this intuitive awareness simply wants to be happy.

160
00:19:56,513 --> 00:19:58,917
It has extraordinary innocence.

161
00:19:59,404 --> 00:20:04,250
It doesn't start from a place of hatred or aversion or anything.

162
00:20:04,270 --> 00:20:09,478
It just starts from a very simple place of just wanting to be happy.

163
00:20:09,939 --> 00:20:10,358
That's all.

164
00:20:12,121 --> 00:20:20,352
And because of that, it identifies with what's actually happening through this primary identification.

165
00:20:21,753 --> 00:20:24,196
And if...

166
00:20:24,717 --> 00:20:37,215
It's because the self, because of aging and death, especially death, that this sense of self feels so unsure.

167
00:20:39,259 --> 00:20:40,441
That's the problem.

168
00:20:40,461 --> 00:20:47,751
The self knows, we know, we, you, me, we know that come death, that's it.

169
00:20:48,794 --> 00:20:52,159
The body, everything will just drop away.

170
00:20:52,375 --> 00:20:57,602
So there's this underlying anxiety to life.

171
00:20:57,622 --> 00:21:05,232
And this underlying fear of death is driving us to make ourselves feel safe.

172
00:21:05,252 --> 00:21:14,645
And we feel safe when we've accumulated masses of wealth, hundreds of friends, racks of DVDs.

173
00:21:15,307 --> 00:21:21,015
I mean, anything that makes us feel comfortable and safe, you see.

174
00:21:21,281 --> 00:21:27,961
Having done that, of course, we have to guard this stuff because everybody else wants what I've got.

175
00:21:28,903 --> 00:21:36,085
And so there's always an aversion to anybody who looks like taking what I've got.

176
00:21:36,705 --> 00:21:47,700
So there's your three fundamental attitudes to life arising from this initial delusion, which is completely innocent, right?

177
00:21:47,720 --> 00:21:50,423
You have no ill will to it at all.

178
00:21:51,243 --> 00:21:59,575
One thing to be happy, and we end up being anxious, averse, and greedy.

179
00:22:00,989 --> 00:22:06,316
And then of course because of those attitudes we start doing things.

180
00:22:06,396 --> 00:22:11,423
We start doing things which are unwholesome, unskillful.

181
00:22:12,404 --> 00:22:19,555
And when we do that we start having the secondary level of guilt and shame and remorse.

182
00:22:21,796 --> 00:22:36,917
Now, the point of escape from that delusive action is not the I, because by the time you get to I, you're lost.

183
00:22:37,318 --> 00:22:40,182
It's catching the wanting, it's catching the desire.

184
00:22:41,164 --> 00:22:46,031
So here, every morning, we've been chanting Dependent Origination.

185
00:22:46,618 --> 00:22:51,269
And that's part of the teaching of the second noble truth, desire.

186
00:22:51,489 --> 00:22:52,351
It comes in there.

187
00:22:53,353 --> 00:23:03,935
And what the Buddha is pointing out is that at first there comes some sort of sense-based information.

188
00:23:05,553 --> 00:23:19,468
So we might walk into the diamond room and we can see our lives fall on a kettle and immediately this brings up the idea of tea.

189
00:23:20,710 --> 00:23:25,134
Now that happens quite naturally because of our past connection with kettles and tea.

190
00:23:26,076 --> 00:23:27,576
You can't stop that happening.

191
00:23:27,798 --> 00:23:31,662
It's just within the whole memory base that we've developed.

192
00:23:32,282 --> 00:23:35,625
And then, of course, there comes the desire.

193
00:23:35,645 --> 00:23:37,007
See, that's what we've been looking at.

194
00:23:37,027 --> 00:23:39,430
We've been looking at this desire, want.

195
00:23:40,631 --> 00:23:40,951
Want.

196
00:23:42,653 --> 00:23:45,255
Sorry, I'll go back a step.

197
00:23:45,275 --> 00:23:52,141
First of all, there's just that initial information that comes in of the kettle.

198
00:23:52,161 --> 00:23:54,644
And through that, the memory of the tea.

199
00:23:56,424 --> 00:23:59,167
That's when we get down to our...

200
00:23:59,501 --> 00:24:04,527
basic experience through the body or through the mind.

201
00:24:05,107 --> 00:24:14,896
So for instance, you know, when I've said, first of all, we might use the word pain, but when we go into the pain, we don't find pain, we just find sensations.

202
00:24:15,597 --> 00:24:17,579
So it's the same with anything we look at.

203
00:24:17,619 --> 00:24:24,747
As soon as we see something or hear something, there's always that neutral base of information that comes in.

204
00:24:24,767 --> 00:24:29,491
But then there is a description of it of either being pleasant or unpleasant.

205
00:24:30,265 --> 00:24:34,731
And that's the life, that's what we base our attraction on.

206
00:24:34,751 --> 00:24:37,036
If it's unpleasant, we want to get rid of it.

207
00:24:37,056 --> 00:24:39,338
And if it's pleasant, we want to get it.

208
00:24:40,320 --> 00:24:45,169
So that's the process in our psychology, that we see the kettle.

209
00:24:45,288 --> 00:24:46,750
The kettle is given a meaning.

210
00:24:47,412 --> 00:24:49,796
And then it's connected with tea.

211
00:24:50,877 --> 00:24:53,101
And then the idea that, ooh, tea is nice.

212
00:24:54,923 --> 00:24:57,268
And then there comes want.

213
00:24:58,075 --> 00:25:02,220
And only then do you get the I want.

214
00:25:03,521 --> 00:25:13,694
Now this is really, really, really important to see, because if the I came first in the process, there could not be an escape.

215
00:25:13,714 --> 00:25:16,538
Because the I is a signal of delusion.

216
00:25:17,519 --> 00:25:20,403
It's only because the sense of I comes last,

217
00:25:20,653 --> 00:25:23,941
That where you can see the process, that there's an escape.

218
00:25:24,401 --> 00:25:27,728
And the escape is at that point of seeing the wanting.

219
00:25:28,710 --> 00:25:37,086
At that point you can discern, you can say to yourself, well, is this time for tea or am I being greedy, you see?

220
00:25:37,827 --> 00:25:42,897
Now, at that point you have a so-called choice, right?

221
00:25:43,250 --> 00:25:54,339
And this is one of those little areas where we in the West get a little confused because we have this idea of free will.

222
00:25:54,400 --> 00:26:04,410
Free will is a construct which comes from Christianity and it's based on Saint Augustine, he was the one who defined it.

223
00:26:04,430 --> 00:26:10,095
And it's defined because God has created human beings to love him.

224
00:26:10,576 --> 00:26:13,137
But what sort of love is it if it's conditioned?

225
00:26:13,522 --> 00:26:17,288
So a human being has to have the freedom to love him or not.

226
00:26:17,308 --> 00:26:21,275
And when they choose to love God, then of course he feels loved.

227
00:26:21,895 --> 00:26:25,801
You can't create something to love him and then feel loved by him.

228
00:26:26,462 --> 00:26:27,765
There's something false about that.

229
00:26:28,205 --> 00:26:30,930
So the human being has this freedom.

230
00:26:31,671 --> 00:26:41,606
And what you get from that is that this free will somehow stands apart from conditioning.

231
00:26:42,311 --> 00:26:52,712
And that's where, there's no other culture that I know, it's definitely not in the East, the idea that you have a free-floating free will.

232
00:26:54,717 --> 00:26:58,464
What you have in the East is discernment.

233
00:26:58,968 --> 00:27:18,990
You can see that something is right or wrong, and then you can choose, but your choice will be based upon your conditioning as to whether you're going to allow yourself to do something which is harmful to yourself or others, or good for yourself or others.

234
00:27:19,912 --> 00:27:27,000
And through the power of discernment, one tends to move towards what is beautiful, what is good for you.

235
00:27:28,178 --> 00:27:31,643
So, it's like going for a walk.

236
00:27:32,084 --> 00:27:45,324
If you go for a walk, and you're going from here to Ennis, there's a path, and you follow the path, and then sometimes you get distracted, and you wander off somewhere, and you get lost, you have to put your compass out, and you think, well, I'm going to go back on the path, or I'm going to keep being lost.

237
00:27:45,723 --> 00:27:48,608
You don't have to go back on the path to come back on the path.

238
00:27:48,949 --> 00:27:56,160
You come to a path, and the map isn't so clear, and the path seems to bifurcate, and you think, where am I going to go?

239
00:27:56,140 --> 00:27:58,061
So you think, well, I'm not sure.

240
00:27:58,082 --> 00:28:01,724
So you try one path, and you end up in a ditch, and you think, oh, this is not the path.

241
00:28:02,026 --> 00:28:04,127
And you come back to where you were, and you try that.

242
00:28:04,488 --> 00:28:10,074
And that's the process of liberation in Buddhist terms.

243
00:28:10,713 --> 00:28:12,756
There isn't actually any free will.

244
00:28:14,298 --> 00:28:16,720
What there is, is a discernment.

245
00:28:17,220 --> 00:28:23,987
Through your lack of it, you make a right decision one way or the other.

246
00:28:25,604 --> 00:28:51,233
So, just to go back to that crucial point, if the I came first, and then you had wanting, and then you had nice ice cream, and then you had the information that there was ice cream in the fridge, there'd be no escape.

247
00:28:51,253 --> 00:28:55,137
Because you'd identify right from the beginning of the process.

248
00:28:55,490 --> 00:29:00,836
It's the fact that the identification comes at the end of the process that the escape is possible.

249
00:29:01,917 --> 00:29:10,248
Now, there's nothing in Indian literature at the time that expresses that depth of understanding of human psychology.

250
00:29:10,828 --> 00:29:21,362
It's extraordinarily new and something which came out of the Buddha's own careful investigation of his suffering.

251
00:29:24,785 --> 00:29:41,882
Now, just to skip the next one, which is the good news, and there is actually this faith in suffering, a complete faith in suffering, the path then, the Eightfold Path, is a way of him expressing how this has to become totally systemic.

252
00:29:42,217 --> 00:30:12,207
you can't if you split the human being into different parts then all you get is at worst is a sort of for want of a better word a schizophrenic person so if they if one part of us knows that we shouldn't be eating all this ice cream and the other part says well we should be then there's going to be this internal battle all the time

253
00:30:12,388 --> 00:30:18,617
Somehow, there has to be a purification of our intentions.

254
00:30:19,259 --> 00:30:20,621
And that's, of course, where it works.

255
00:30:21,201 --> 00:30:27,211
So, knowing, for instance, that too much ice cream is not good for us is only the beginning of the process.

256
00:30:27,250 --> 00:30:34,122
Then we have to restrain and not buy so much ice cream.

257
00:30:34,662 --> 00:30:36,605
It's as simple as that.

258
00:30:36,625 --> 00:30:40,371
And keep away from the ice cream counter when we go to the...

259
00:30:40,351 --> 00:30:42,433
Supermarket.

260
00:30:43,134 --> 00:30:50,967
It's like it has to come into your specific daily practice, so that everything we're doing has to be questioned.

261
00:30:51,928 --> 00:30:52,709
Is this good for me?

262
00:30:52,848 --> 00:30:53,410
Is it wholesome?

263
00:30:53,430 --> 00:30:54,171
Is it not wholesome?

264
00:30:55,053 --> 00:31:00,941
And one little trick that you can try is to ask yourself, what would the Buddha do?

265
00:31:01,682 --> 00:31:10,154
Now that's not entirely reliable, but at least it gives us, it connects us to an archetype which is in us of

266
00:31:13,897 --> 00:31:14,258
You see?

267
00:31:14,939 --> 00:31:15,940
You could do it with anybody.

268
00:31:16,000 --> 00:31:17,021
Would Christ do it?

269
00:31:17,041 --> 00:31:18,603
Would Saint Francis do it?

270
00:31:18,644 --> 00:31:19,324
You know what I mean?

271
00:31:19,785 --> 00:31:31,598
Because we know these stories of people and they've created within us an idea, an archetype of what it is to be holy, to be saintly, to be good, yeah?

272
00:31:31,618 --> 00:31:33,200
To be liberated and all that.

273
00:31:33,601 --> 00:31:37,925
So often when you sit there and you think, well, should I be watching this TV program?

274
00:31:38,385 --> 00:31:39,488
I'll ask the Buddha.

275
00:31:39,508 --> 00:31:39,788
No.

276
00:31:40,477 --> 00:31:48,308
It doesn't mean to say that you won't, but at least there's a certain level of truth there about it.

277
00:31:49,230 --> 00:32:05,236
And of course, if you say, well, yeah, the Buddha wasn't where I am, then at least you acknowledge your weakness, and then you might make a determination that the next time the program's on, you'll find something else to do.

278
00:32:05,256 --> 00:32:06,298
Take a walk or something.

279
00:32:07,662 --> 00:32:16,171
So that business of a systemic process begins with this discernment.

280
00:32:17,172 --> 00:32:24,159
And specifically the Buddha has pointed to this process of wrong desiring.

281
00:32:25,800 --> 00:32:37,432
Now, when a desire comes, whatever it is, whatever negative desire comes,

282
00:32:37,665 --> 00:32:39,428
It's substantive.

283
00:32:39,448 --> 00:32:44,755
It becomes something real for us when we identify with it.

284
00:32:44,775 --> 00:32:49,300
So when I say I hate that person, that feels pretty real.

285
00:32:49,921 --> 00:32:51,282
I'm angry with that person.

286
00:32:51,462 --> 00:32:52,084
I'm angry with him.

287
00:32:52,664 --> 00:32:57,892
But what we're learning to say is there is an aversion towards that person.

288
00:32:58,011 --> 00:32:58,712
There is.

289
00:32:58,732 --> 00:33:02,257
So already I'm pulling myself out of it.

290
00:33:02,277 --> 00:33:03,858
I'm not identifying with this thing.

291
00:33:04,210 --> 00:33:17,728
And therefore it loses its power over me in the sense of making me say something hateful or even think something hateful if it's good enough and definitely stopping me from doing something hateful.

292
00:33:17,748 --> 00:33:26,380
Now, this energy, if you look at it like the weather, you know, like little storms and then suddenly the sun comes out.

293
00:33:26,900 --> 00:33:33,288
If you just see the heart and the mind and even the body as just energy, forms of energy,

294
00:33:33,421 --> 00:33:42,393
then what we discover is that any negative energy we have will transform into its opposite.

295
00:33:43,034 --> 00:33:44,536
It will just happen.

296
00:33:44,556 --> 00:33:51,605
Because no energy is actually lost, whether that's a physical truth or not, it's definitely a mental truth.

297
00:33:52,047 --> 00:33:53,167
No energy is lost.

298
00:33:53,888 --> 00:33:54,769
It's transformed.

299
00:33:55,050 --> 00:33:57,354
And frankly, I much prefer the word...

300
00:33:58,115 --> 00:34:00,458
It's got out of my head...

301
00:34:03,694 --> 00:34:14,186
which is to move chemically from a solid directly into a gas without going through the medium of a liquid.

302
00:34:14,907 --> 00:34:27,862
So when we feel aversion towards somebody, if we just stay with it, stay with it, stay with it, as it melts, as it were, as it melts, you're able to put yourself in the other person's shoes.

303
00:34:28,501 --> 00:34:37,793
And immediately a sense of compassion and some form of connection, which we might call love, arises quite naturally.

304
00:34:37,813 --> 00:34:47,425
Because when anybody does anything hateful to us, they themselves will have their own internal problems, psychological problems.

305
00:34:49,869 --> 00:34:54,474
I remember, and this happened to me very, very clearly on one occasion,

306
00:34:55,027 --> 00:35:00,856
when I got into quite an adverse state with my teacher, who was a lovely Burmese monk.

307
00:35:01,056 --> 00:35:08,208
And I was very upset with him, for various reasons.

308
00:35:08,329 --> 00:35:14,097
It wasn't completely wrong, but definitely I got into a very strong aversion.

309
00:35:14,818 --> 00:35:20,967
And it's quite remarkable, because I was doing a personal retreat in Wales,

310
00:35:20,947 --> 00:35:46,550
a long time ago now, but I remember sitting there and doing exactly that, just not indulging, you know, through storylines, my reasons for hating and wanting to hang you, but to sit just with the feeling of this very raw sort of frustration and anger and everything else down there.

311
00:35:46,835 --> 00:35:59,976
And then to my surprise, you see, I'm just watching this, I'm just feeling it, you know, I'm not extending any hateful thoughts towards it, but staying entirely with the emotional content.

312
00:36:00,637 --> 00:36:06,547
I actually saw it just completely just transform into compassion.

313
00:36:07,152 --> 00:36:08,875
And it just happened in front of my eyes.

314
00:36:09,394 --> 00:36:13,501
And when that happens to you, then you know that's what's happening all the time.

315
00:36:14,342 --> 00:36:16,525
Even if it's not so obvious or distinct.

316
00:36:17,367 --> 00:36:29,244
Over the period of time, if you don't just react with anger, but stay with it, if you sit in your anxiety,

317
00:36:29,224 --> 00:36:37,693
And just sit with that anxiety as it is, without it developing storylines of horror for us.

318
00:36:38,335 --> 00:36:43,440
And remember that something like 99% of all we're anxious about never actually happens.

319
00:36:44,222 --> 00:36:50,108
Once we drive that home, you see, and what you see is that it transfers to its opposite.

320
00:36:51,610 --> 00:36:54,472
One of the things that everybody suffers from

321
00:36:54,655 --> 00:37:00,130
one occasion of that, at different depths, is of course loneliness, feeling of loneliness.

322
00:37:01,052 --> 00:37:06,708
And loneliness can be very painful, a feeling of not being well.

323
00:37:06,809 --> 00:37:10,099
I'm no good and everybody hates me, and rightly so.

324
00:37:11,260 --> 00:37:12,641
and all that stuff.

325
00:37:14,244 --> 00:37:25,677
Now, if you keep that train of thought going, of course, then you're reinforcing that feeling of isolation, of being alone in that bad sense, in that unwholesome sense.

326
00:37:26,818 --> 00:37:35,309
But if you sit with it, if you just stay with it, you see, then very slowly, you see, as it decreases,

327
00:37:35,407 --> 00:37:45,547
When it ends, when it ends, when it comes to an end, what you end up with is a transformation of that moment into a sense of solitude.

328
00:37:46,590 --> 00:37:48,414
Just pure solitude.

329
00:37:48,434 --> 00:37:52,422
Which is to be completely happy just being with yourself.

330
00:37:53,195 --> 00:38:21,378
and these things you can practice at any time and what this does is if you do that sort of thing and take it to that point even if it takes days to get to that point take it to that point then it builds up in you a real confidence to stay with what is so painful at times within us and you know that it will pass and the real insight is that the heart heals itself

331
00:38:22,034 --> 00:38:27,822
And that's the amazing thing, that you don't have to do anything.

332
00:38:27,842 --> 00:38:38,599
It's just like water, if you keep swirling it around with a whisk and it keeps moving, if you take the whisk out, the water naturally settles to a stasis, to appeasement.

333
00:38:39,041 --> 00:38:41,224
And that's the natural state of the heart.

334
00:38:41,608 --> 00:38:52,782
So when we say that this awareness, this intuitive awareness, begins from a point of innocence, it begins from that point where nothing is ruffling it.

335
00:38:53,242 --> 00:38:55,644
But then it has this delusive moment.

336
00:38:58,047 --> 00:39:00,590
Every moment of our lives has this delusive moment.

337
00:39:00,630 --> 00:39:04,114
The idea of the self is always a substrate in everything we do.

338
00:39:04,856 --> 00:39:09,800
All we can notice is how it's drawing us into suffering and pull back from that.

339
00:39:11,063 --> 00:39:11,143
See?

340
00:39:11,815 --> 00:39:17,003
If I see I'm getting anxious about something, I just go, stay in the anxiety.

341
00:39:17,023 --> 00:39:21,188
Often when the anxiety passes, you find there was nothing to be anxious about.

342
00:39:23,331 --> 00:39:29,221
So our practice is to be as best as we can all the day.

343
00:39:29,280 --> 00:39:34,929
From the time we wake up to the time we fall asleep is to be aware of how the mind is moving.

344
00:39:36,331 --> 00:39:39,695
Not to get anxious about it, if we miss it.

345
00:39:43,135 --> 00:39:59,489
just makes us more and more keenly aware of what we're doing and this idea of going slow obviously we can't go as slow as this in daily life but really just to keep stopping and to take our time to stop and take our time

346
00:39:59,706 --> 00:40:04,713
And often we think that, especially in certain work situations, that's going to make us inefficient.

347
00:40:05,255 --> 00:40:08,920
We may find, actually, that by doing that, we're actually more efficient.

348
00:40:09,601 --> 00:40:12,864
Because a lot of our inefficiency is done because of rushing.

349
00:40:14,427 --> 00:40:15,489
Forgetting your keys.

350
00:40:18,532 --> 00:40:25,943
We create so much bother for ourselves just being in this constant state of rushing.

351
00:40:25,963 --> 00:40:28,025
So...

352
00:40:31,347 --> 00:40:40,596
We've come to a point now, then, where, by the way, the Buddha never offers any solution to the question as to why this should happen in the first place.

353
00:40:41,637 --> 00:40:52,909
You know, why we're here in the first place, why we've entered into this life form right at the beginning, because there's no seeable beginning to karma.

354
00:40:53,208 --> 00:40:54,750
The Buddha says it's always been here.

355
00:40:55,771 --> 00:41:01,336
You know, the idea of cause and effect, cause and effect, is endless, you know.

356
00:41:02,025 --> 00:41:06,135
Although in some religions they might talk about the first cause.

357
00:41:06,597 --> 00:41:08,842
That is essentially illogical.

358
00:41:09,603 --> 00:41:10,827
There is no first cause.

359
00:41:10,847 --> 00:41:11,489
It just is.

360
00:41:11,509 --> 00:41:13,253
This is the way it is all the time.

361
00:41:14,275 --> 00:41:19,849
And if you think of it in terms of a stretch of time, it seems...

362
00:41:20,385 --> 00:41:26,492
It seems unimaginable, you know, going this way forever and then going that way forever.

363
00:41:27,132 --> 00:41:34,820
But if you take it moment to moment, that things are just arising and passing away, there's no reason to think that ever started or ever stops.

364
00:41:36,963 --> 00:41:39,166
Time, remember, is a mental construct.

365
00:41:39,246 --> 00:41:41,068
We build up some idea of history.

366
00:41:41,628 --> 00:41:46,713
But actually, all that's happening is this, and this, and this.

367
00:41:49,715 --> 00:42:04,487
So we can presume that the Buddha was very anxious before his liberation about this whole problem.

368
00:42:04,507 --> 00:42:07,554
And in investigating this process,

369
00:42:08,512 --> 00:42:24,771
he discovers something which is quite miraculous because up until then there had been some hints about it and the Upanishads that were being written were definitely moving in the same direction.

370
00:42:25,510 --> 00:42:34,101
But he came across this state which was outside the whole process of manifestation.

371
00:42:35,081 --> 00:42:35,641
Outside it.

372
00:42:36,043 --> 00:42:38,065
And yet, within it,

373
00:42:39,175 --> 00:42:44,702
So when he became enlightened he didn't sort of disappear in a puff of smoke.

374
00:42:45,403 --> 00:42:47,447
It wasn't as though he went somewhere else.

375
00:42:48,228 --> 00:42:55,259
He still stayed in the body and he still got up and he still ate and he probably still peed.

376
00:42:55,278 --> 00:42:55,980
I'm sure he peed.

377
00:42:56,420 --> 00:42:58,463
And he did all the things that a human being did.

378
00:42:59,143 --> 00:43:01,487
And he began to speak about his understandings.

379
00:43:02,489 --> 00:43:07,697
And yet he was saying to people that there is an end to suffering and he didn't suffer.

380
00:43:08,891 --> 00:43:17,340
Now, I don't know of any Western psychoanalytic or psychological school which makes that statement.

381
00:43:18,561 --> 00:43:28,710
All Western schools talk about an accommodation, you know, that you can get better, you can be at ease with it, get to a certain place, but you'll never get rid of anxiety.

382
00:43:29,351 --> 00:43:30,813
You'll never get rid of fear.

383
00:43:31,492 --> 00:43:36,637
I mean, I've read this quite clearly in books on psychotherapy and psychology.

384
00:43:36,617 --> 00:43:40,601
And, like in that lovely book, feel the fear and do it anyway.

385
00:43:40,641 --> 00:43:43,405
You could say that about anything.

386
00:43:43,565 --> 00:43:45,246
Feel the depression and do it anyway.

387
00:43:45,606 --> 00:43:46,728
It doesn't just work for fear.

388
00:43:47,268 --> 00:43:56,257
And the reason, of course, why they can't go beyond that is because they've not seen the core problem, which is the problem of identity.

389
00:43:58,418 --> 00:44:06,286
Once the Buddha had broken through the illusion of identity, he discovered a different state.

390
00:44:06,672 --> 00:44:13,811
And in the actual formation of the Noble Truth, it just says there is an end to suffering.

391
00:44:13,831 --> 00:44:14,193
All's gone.

392
00:44:15,436 --> 00:44:18,284
Later, it's given this word, Nibbāna.

393
00:44:18,467 --> 00:44:27,222
Nirvana is a state which is transcendent of a phenomenal world.

394
00:44:28,264 --> 00:44:33,873
In other words, in Nirvana you don't find anything of this phenomenal world.

395
00:44:33,932 --> 00:44:34,775
What do we mean by that?

396
00:44:35,215 --> 00:44:36,677
There's no thinking.

397
00:44:36,697 --> 00:44:38,079
There's no images.

398
00:44:38,059 --> 00:44:44,228
Interesting enough, even though we talk about the bliss of Nibbana, the peace of Nibbana, there's no mental state.

399
00:44:45,068 --> 00:44:46,630
There's no emotions.

400
00:44:46,650 --> 00:44:47,693
There's definitely no body.

401
00:44:48,293 --> 00:44:49,655
There's no sensations and feelings.

402
00:44:51,117 --> 00:44:56,224
The whole thing disappears within that state of Nibbana.

403
00:44:56,244 --> 00:45:06,496
Now, there's a kernel experience of that state, but then that state re-enters into this psychophysical organism.

404
00:45:07,135 --> 00:45:09,056
and begins to express his wisdom.

405
00:45:09,918 --> 00:45:20,268
So the Buddha, having achieved this understanding, this experience of what is transcendental, re-enters into this form and begins his ministry.

406
00:45:24,871 --> 00:45:35,623
Now, in early, in the Theravada Buddhism, this state of Nibbana is

407
00:45:35,992 --> 00:45:42,422
tended to be expressed quite negatively, because it's describing what's not there.

408
00:45:43,083 --> 00:45:54,340
And there are some very collected sayings of the Buddha, where he talks about, for instance, well, we repeat one of them, that is, that which is not brought doesn't die.

409
00:45:55,222 --> 00:45:59,467
There's one where he talks about the sphere of experience, the sphere of

410
00:45:59,835 --> 00:46:04,405
So spheres, in the Buddha's understanding, are to do with your sense bases.

411
00:46:04,425 --> 00:46:09,614
So there's a visual sphere, which cannot be connected with the audio sphere.

412
00:46:09,655 --> 00:46:11,257
They're two different sense bases.

413
00:46:11,297 --> 00:46:13,643
They're two different ways of experiencing life.

414
00:46:14,483 --> 00:46:22,719
There's the mental sphere, but he says there is a sphere where there's no sun, no moon, no coming, no going, etc., etc.

415
00:46:22,920 --> 00:46:31,217
So he's pointing to something which is quite transcendent of this particular manifestation called world.

416
00:46:31,958 --> 00:46:34,264
He talks about it as an island.

417
00:46:38,750 --> 00:46:39,931
consciousness.

418
00:46:41,094 --> 00:46:52,313
So the Buddha, like anybody who has a new idea or new discovery, is always lost for words because the present vocabulary doesn't include the understanding.

419
00:46:52,333 --> 00:47:04,452
So in the verse, in the victory verse that we chant, he actually uses the word citta, asantaka, the unconditioned consciousness, for want of a better word.

420
00:47:04,956 --> 00:47:11,490
So he's using citta, which now, which for those of you who know, in the Abhidhamma, refers to the mind.

421
00:47:12,072 --> 00:47:15,137
But obviously, the mind can't be unconditioned.

422
00:47:15,157 --> 00:47:17,121
The mind is conditioned.

423
00:47:17,141 --> 00:47:25,159
So he's pointing to something which knows, citta means that which knows, which is not conditioned.

424
00:47:25,561 --> 00:47:31,228
And then he talks about it as a consciousness and uses the word vijnana.

425
00:47:31,248 --> 00:47:36,916
For those of you who know, that's the vijnana, the consciousness of the five aggregates.

426
00:47:37,898 --> 00:47:45,889
Now, it can't be that vijnana because he talks about it as not touched by any of these senses.

427
00:47:47,992 --> 00:47:52,800
It doesn't belong to the sphere of the sense bases, which includes the mind and heart.

428
00:47:53,168 --> 00:47:56,530
And it's without boundary.

429
00:47:56,550 --> 00:47:58,393
It's phenomena that creates boundaries.

430
00:47:58,413 --> 00:48:00,434
It's the walls that create the boundary of this.

431
00:48:01,436 --> 00:48:03,657
But there's a conscious world that doesn't have that boundary.

432
00:48:03,677 --> 00:48:11,284
And in all directions, full of light, just this is the end of suffering.

433
00:48:11,304 --> 00:48:21,554
Now the reason I'm pointing to that is because in later Buddhism, the accent moved away from the experience to what was

434
00:48:21,940 --> 00:48:24,983
What was it that knew the experience?

435
00:48:25,043 --> 00:48:27,264
What was it that experienced the experience?

436
00:48:28,126 --> 00:48:42,661
And that's when you get words like the big mind, the Buddha, the Buddha within.

437
00:48:43,902 --> 00:48:48,065
There's another one too that normally comes to mind, it's gone.

438
00:48:49,530 --> 00:49:00,460
Both of these ways of looking at this transcendent state is one from the point of view of experience and one point of view that the experience is known.

439
00:49:01,001 --> 00:49:02,623
Buddha is the one who knows.

440
00:49:03,744 --> 00:49:05,246
Now, where is it?

441
00:49:07,327 --> 00:49:10,070
Where is this experience we've found?

442
00:49:11,512 --> 00:49:17,918
Whenever we meditate and we take the position of the observer within us, we meditate.

443
00:49:18,590 --> 00:49:38,349
Because when you're the observer, you have pulled yourself out of that identity with what's going on within you, whether it be a sensation or a feeling coming from the body, an emotion or a mood that you can sense within you, a thought which you might see, but definitely images.

444
00:49:38,889 --> 00:49:48,579
So you've found a place which is transcendent of the body, and yet directly within it.

445
00:49:49,014 --> 00:50:00,429
So that's why I keep saying to people, when the sense of the observer is very, very clear to you, see, after you finish the meditation, just ask yourself, what was it like being there?

446
00:50:05,115 --> 00:50:17,030
Now, if you say to yourself, that's all right, that's good, yeah, but I'd rather be in there, having a good time, in Buddhist terms, that's the level of delusion.

447
00:50:18,277 --> 00:50:29,753
The more you seek that inner peace, that inner silence, the more it's telling you that you are finding a different relationship with the world.

448
00:50:30,414 --> 00:50:33,858
That different relationship with the world is not to negate the world.

449
00:50:34,659 --> 00:50:39,306
You know, we try to make a distinction between indulging something and enjoying something.

450
00:50:39,708 --> 00:50:45,394
That relationship now is one of connection.

451
00:50:46,115 --> 00:50:47,838
And connection means love.

452
00:50:47,878 --> 00:50:51,643
It draws you into a loving connection with the world.

453
00:50:52,184 --> 00:51:04,500
And depending on the situation, it's either the love that we associate with friendship, or the love that we associate with suffering, which expresses our compassion, or the love that expresses itself as love.

454
00:51:06,403 --> 00:51:09,751
rejoicing in somebody else's happiness, sympathetic joy.

455
00:51:10,753 --> 00:51:17,809
And all the rest of it, all the virtues that you can think of, are the expressions of that wisdom into the world.

456
00:51:19,894 --> 00:51:23,382
So, the prognosis is very good.

457
00:51:28,965 --> 00:51:40,545
words of being of some assistance may you by your joyful and committed practice soon arrive at that place of pure joy sooner rather than later

